FLYING TOASTERS GROW PROPS. Delrina Corp., locked in legislative conflict
with Berkeley Systems Inc. over a flying toaster screen-saver program, has
a new plan. Its "Opus 'n Bill" toasters will now be propeller-driven. "I
just wish they would choose their own appliance, said a Berkeley marketing
vp. "I wouldn't mind at all if they decided to do a flying blender." (Wall
Street Journal 10/12/93 B5)

NO CHECKOUT LINES. A Long Island company has come up with a solution to
long checkout lines in grocery stores. It's designed a hand-held computer
about the size of a telephone receiver that customers would use to scan
products as they put them in their grocery carts. They would then bag their
own groceries, wait a minute for the device to total up the bill, and pay
on the way out. The drawback -- how to detect shoppers who "forget" to scan
items. (St. Petersburg Times 10/12/93 A1)

ELECTRONIC STYLE.  Meckler has published a 65-page book called "Electronic
Style:  A Guide to Citing Electronic Information," which helps scholars
cite information in a way that will make it easier for other scholars to
find the electronic sources for them.  It costs $15 and is available from
Meckler Publ., 11 Ferry Lane West, Westport, CT 06880.

NOTE TAKING.  Lotus Notes, which allows groups of workers to communicate
over pc networks, has becoming the defining product of Lotus and is "a
software maker's dream:  a hot product with no competition." (New York
Times 10/13/93 C1)

NOVELL TRANSFERRING UNIX RIGHTS. Novell Inc. will transfer Unix operating
system trademark rights to X/Open Co., a nonprofit consortium that helps
set industry standards. The agreement allows any company to use the Unix
name, as long as its software complies with the new specifications. (Wall
Street Journal 10/12/93 B6)

DIGITAL UNVEILS NEW WORKSTATION. Digital Equipment Corp. announced a new
top-of-the-line workstation that will be as powerful as the one announced
by IBM last month, at half the price. Digital's model will cost $36,000 as
compared to IBM's $70,000 price tag. (Wall Street Journal 10/12/93 B4)

Subject:      E-D-U-P-A-G-E  10/28/93

WORKPLACE PRIVACY. Sen. Paul Simon has introduced a bill that would force
companies to tell workers ahead of time if they regularly monitor e-mail
messages. Companies would also have to disclose after the fact that they
accessed an employee's hard drive. (Wall Street Journal 10/26/93 A1)

NEW GOALS FOR HIGH-PERFORMANCE COMPUTING. A panel of researchers has
outlined a new vision for NSF's role in promoting high-performance
computing activities. The panel, chaired by Lewis Branscomb, urged NSF to:
establish a teraflop computing facility, double its financial investment in
workstations for researchers, increase its support for mid-range computers,
and reaffirm its support for the four national supercomputer centers.
(Chronicle of Higher Education 10/27/93 A20)

NEW MAC SPORTS BUILT-IN TV. Apple's new Macintosh TV incorporates a
Macintosh computer, a television and a stereo CD player all in one unit.
The new product is geared toward the home and educational market, and will
be available at selected retail stores, college campuses and through the
Apple Catalog. (Wall Street Journal 10/26/93 B2)

CRAY UNVEILS DOWNSIZED SUPERCOMPUTER. Cray Research is moving into the
commercial computing market with a downsized version of its supercomputer.
The Cray Superserver 6400 is based on Sun Microsystem's Sparc chip and runs
software based on Sun's Solaris operating system. (Wall Street Journal
10/26/93 B7)

OFFICE IN THE SKY. In an effort to woo the lucrative business passenger,
aircraft maker McDonnell Douglas has designed several on-board office
configurations, complete with desks, fax machines, computers, printers and
telephones. So far, none of the airlines have ordered an airborne office,
but American Airlines and Delta are both considering the "office in the
sky" as part of their long-term strategies. (Wall Street Journal 10/27/93
B1)

INTEL'S BIG FLASH. Intel Corp. "scooped major rivals" by announcing volume
shipments of its flash chips -- memory chips that can retain data in the
absence of electrical power, and can be erased and reprogrammed relatively
easily. The company expects to ship 33 million flash chips in 1993, up from
15 million in 1992, and is looking toward sales of 80 million units next
year. (Wall Street Journal 10/28/93 B9)

